[Malawi](/Malawi) &#91;a&#93; &#91;9&#93;, officially recognized as the [Republic of Malawi](/Malawi) &#91;b&#93;, is a [landlocked country](/Landlocked_country) situated in the heart of [Southeastern Africa](/Southeast_Africa). Its geographical confines are defined by [Zambia](/Zambia) to the west, [Tanzania](/Tanzania) to the north and northeast, and [Mozambique](/Mozambique) embracing its eastern, southern, and southwestern flanks. Spanning an expansive 118,484&#160;km 2 (45,747&#160;sq&#160;mi), [Malawi](/Malawi) is home to an estimated population of 22,224,282 as of July 2025 &#91;10&#93;. The nation's administrative and commercial heart beats in [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe), its capital and [largest city](/List_of_cities_in_Malawi), while other significant urban centers include [Blantyre](/Blantyre), [Mzuzu](/Mzuzu), and [Zomba](/Zomba,_Malawi), the latter having once served as the former colonial capital.

The historical narrative of the land now known as [Malawi](/Malawi) is a rich tapestry woven over centuries. Early settlements, dating back to approximately the 10th century, were primarily established by the [Akafula](/Akafula), also referred to as the [Abathwa](/Abathwa), who were [hunter-gatherer](/Hunter-gatherer) communities. Their presence, however, was later overshadowed by successive waves of [Bantu groups](/Bantu_peoples) migrating into the region. These [Bantu](/Bantu_peoples) arrivals, bringing with them advanced agricultural and iron-working techniques, gradually displaced the [Akafula](/Akafula) and subsequently forged a series of influential kingdoms. Among the most prominent were the [Maravi](/Maravi) and [Nkhamanga](/Nkhamanga_Kingdom) kingdoms, which enjoyed periods of significant prosperity and cultural development from the 16th century onwards &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93;.

The late 19th century ushered in a new era as the region fell under the sway of European colonial powers. In 1891, the area was formally colonized by the British, initially designated as the [British Central African Protectorate](/British_Central_Africa_Protectorate). This protectorate was later renamed [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland) in 1907, a designation it would retain for over half a century. A pivotal moment arrived in 1964 when [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland) achieved its [independence](/Independence) under the leadership of Prime Minister [Hastings Banda](/Hastings_Banda), marking its rebirth as [Malawi](/Malawi). Just two years later, in a move that would define the nation's political trajectory for decades, [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) transitioned the country into a [one-party](/One-party_state) presidential republic, assuming the presidency himself. His grip on power solidified further in 1971 when he was controversially declared [president for life](/President_for_life). This initial period of independence was, unfortunately, characterized by [Banda's](/Hastings_Banda) highly repressive dictatorship, a shadow that lingered over the nation for nearly three decades &#91;13&#93; &#91;14&#93; &#91;15&#93;.

The winds of change began to blow in 1993 with the introduction of a [multiparty system](/Multi-party_system), a significant shift from the entrenched authoritarianism. This political liberalization ultimately led to [Banda's](/Hastings_Banda) defeat in the [1994 general election](/1994_Malawian_general_election). Today, [Malawi](/Malawi) stands as a [democratic](/Democracy), [multi-party](/Multi-party_system) republic, guided by an elected president, though its political journey remains, shall we say, *dynamic*. According to the 2024 [V-Dem Democracy indices](/V-Dem_Democracy_indices), [Malawi](/Malawi) is ranked 74th globally as an [electoral democracy](/Electoral_democracy) and an impressive 11th among [African electoral democracies](/Democracy_in_Africa) &#91;16&#93;, a notable achievement given its tumultuous past. The country actively cultivates positive diplomatic relations with a majority of nations and is a committed participant in several key [international organisations](/International_organisation), including the [United Nations](/United_Nations), the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations), the [Southern African Development Community](/Southern_African_Development_Community) (SADC), the [Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa](/Common_Market_for_Eastern_and_Southern_Africa) (COMESA), and the [African Union](/African_Union) (AU), underscoring its role on the global stage.

Despite its political progress, [Malawi](/Malawi) remains one of the world's [least developed countries](/Least_developed_countries). Its [economy](/Economy_of_Malawi) is heavily reliant on [agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Malawi), supporting a largely rural and steadily expanding population. While facing considerable structural challenges, [Malawi](/Malawi) has demonstrably made strides in its economy, education system, and healthcare infrastructure in recent years. However, the nation continues to grapple with a low [life expectancy](/Life_expectancy) and an alarmingly high [infant mortality](/Infant_mortality) rate. The pervasive challenge of [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS) significantly impacts the country, not only by reducing the available labor force but also by demanding substantial government expenditures for treatment and care. The country's population is remarkably diverse, comprising various [native peoples](/Indigenous_peoples), alongside communities of [Asians](/Asian_people) and [Europeans](/Ethnic_groups_in_Europe). A multitude of languages are spoken, though [Christianity](/Christianity) predominates as the primary religion, with the majority identifying as [Protestant](/Protestantism). Encouragingly, a sense of shared [Malawian nationality](/Demographics_of_Malawi) has visibly strengthened over the past few decades, fostering a more unified national identity.

## Etymology

The name "[Malawi](/Malawi)" carries a profound symbolic meaning, translating to "flames" in both the [Chichewa](/Chichewa) and [Chitumbuka](/Chitumbuka) languages. This evocative name was not a historical accident but a deliberate choice. It was selected by the nation's inaugural [president](/President_of_Malawi), [Hastings Kamuzu Banda](/Kamuzu_Banda), at the pivotal moment when the country achieved its full [independence](/Independence) from [Great Britain](/United_Kingdom) in 1964 &#91;17&#93;. The imagery of "flames" is often interpreted as representing the dawn of a new era, the burning passion for freedom, and the vibrant, often fiery, spirit of the [Malawian](/Demographics_of_Malawi) people themselves.

## History

* Main article: [History of Malawi](/History_of_Malawi)

### Pre-colonial history

The [Chongoni Rock Art Area](/Chongoni_Rock_Art_Area) stands as a silent testament to the ancient human presence in the region. Before the arrival of the [Bantu peoples](/Bantu_peoples), the part of [Africa](/Africa) that would eventually become [Malawi](/Malawi) was sparsely populated by scattered groups of [hunter-gatherers](/Hunter-gatherer). These early inhabitants lived off the land, their lives intricately linked to the rhythm of nature. However, around the 10th century CE, the demographic landscape began to shift dramatically with the advent of successive waves of [Bantu peoples](/Bantu_peoples) emigrating from the north &#91;18&#93;. While a significant portion of these [Bantu migrants](/Bantu_peoples) continued their southward journey, some chose to settle in the fertile lands of [Malawi](/Malawi), gradually forming distinct [ethnic groups](/Ethnic_group) unified by common ancestry and shared traditions &#91;19&#93;.

By the year 1500, these burgeoning tribal communities had successfully established several powerful and influential kingdoms. Among these, the [Maravi](/Maravi) kingdom was particularly notable, its dominion stretching impressively from the areas north of what is now [Nkhotakota](/Nkhotakota) all the way to the [Zambezi River](/Zambezi_River) in the south, and from the shores of [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) eastward to the [Luangwa River](/Luangwa_River) in what is now [Zambia](/Zambia). Another significant entity was the [Nkhamanga Kingdom](/Nkhamanga_Kingdom), which also flourished during this period, contributing to a rich pre-colonial history of organized polities and complex societies &#91;20&#93;.

Shortly after 1600, with much of the region under the effective, albeit sometimes fragmented, control of various native rulers, the indigenous tribesmen began to engage with external forces. They encountered, traded with, and even formed strategic alliances with [Portuguese traders](/Portuguese_people) and military personnel who had ventured inland from the coast. This interaction introduced new goods, ideas, and, unfortunately, new forms of exploitation. By 1700, however, the grand [Maravi empire](/Maravi) had fragmented, dissolving into smaller territories, each governed by individual [ethnic groups](/Ethnic_group) &#91;21&#93;. This decentralization made the region more vulnerable to external pressures. The devastating [Indian Ocean slave trade](/Indian_Ocean_slave_trade) reached its brutal zenith in the mid-1800s. During this dark period, it is estimated that approximately 20,000 individuals annually were forcibly enslaved and transported from [Nkhotakota](/Nkhotakota) to [Kilwa](/Kilwa_Kisiwani), where they were then sold into bondage &#91;22&#93;. This harrowing chapter left an indelible mark on the region's demographics and social fabric.

### Colonialisation (1859–1960)

* Main article: [Political history of Malawi](/Political_history_of_Malawi)

The arrival of Scottish missionary and explorer [David Livingstone](/David_Livingstone) at [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) (then famously known as Lake Nyasa) in 1859 marked a turning point. [Livingstone](/David_Livingstone), ever the keen observer, quickly identified the [Shire Highlands](/Shire_Highlands) to the south of the lake as an exceptionally promising area for potential European settlement, a judgment that would dramatically alter the region's destiny. His reports and influence led to the establishment of several [Anglican](/Anglicanism) and [Presbyterian](/Presbyterianism) missions throughout the area during the 1860s and 1870s, bringing with them not only religious doctrine but also European customs and infrastructure. Building on this nascent presence, the [African Lakes](/African_Lakes) Company Limited was founded in 1878 with the explicit aim of creating a robust trade and transport network, further embedding European economic interests. A small but strategically important mission and trading settlement was subsequently established at [Blantyre](/Blantyre) in 1876, and by 1883, a British [Consul](/Consul_(representative)) took up residence there, formalizing British diplomatic presence.

However, British ambitions were not unchallenged. The [Portuguese government](/Portuguese_people) also harbored significant interests in the region, seeking to expand its own colonial claims. To preempt any full-scale Portuguese occupation, the British government dispatched [Harry Johnston](/Harry_Johnston) as British consul, armed with clear instructions: to forge treaties with local rulers in areas lying beyond existing Portuguese jurisdiction &#91;23&#93;, a classic maneuver in the "Scramble for Africa."

In 1889, the British officially declared a [protectorate](/Protectorate) over the [Shire Highlands](/Shire_Highlands). This was quickly expanded in 1891 to encompass the entirety of what is now modern-day [Malawi](/Malawi), officially designating it as the [British Central Africa Protectorate](/British_Central_Africa_Protectorate) &#91;24&#93;. In 1907, the protectorate underwent another name change, becoming [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland), a moniker it would retain throughout the remainder of its British colonial rule &#91;25&#93;. The administration of this vast territory, often cited as an example of the "Thin White Line" of colonial authority in [Africa](/Africa), was remarkably lean, almost comically so. The colonial government of [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland), established in 1891, was allocated a meager budget of £10,000 (in 1891 nominal value) per year. This sum was deemed sufficient to employ a mere ten European civilians, two military officers, seventy [Punjabi Sikhs](/Sikhs), and eighty-five [Zanzibar porters](/Porter_(carrier)) &#91;26&#93;. These few individuals were then expected to administer and police a territory spanning approximately 94,000&#160;square kilometers, inhabited by between one and two million people. One might wonder what level of "administration" was truly possible with such a skeletal crew. In that same year, the abhorrent practice of [slavery](/Slavery_in_Africa) within the protectorate was brought to a complete cessation, a significant, if belated, humanitarian achievement.

By 1944, a growing desire for self-determination led to the formation of the [Nyasaland African Congress](/Nyasaland_African_Congress) (NAC) by the indigenous Africans of [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland). Their primary objective was to advocate for local interests and articulate the grievances of the African population directly to the British government &#91;27&#93;. A controversial decision in 1953 saw Britain link [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland) with Northern and Southern [Rhodesia](/Rhodesia) to form the [Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland](/Federation_of_Rhodesia_and_Nyasaland), often abbreviated as the Central African Federation (CAF) &#91;25&#93;. This federation was created for primarily political reasons &#91;28&#93;, largely without the consent of the African majority, and despite its semi-independent status, it immediately sparked widespread opposition from African nationalists. The NAC, capitalizing on this discontent, rapidly gained popular support, becoming a powerful voice for change. A particularly influential opponent of the CAF was [Hastings Banda](/Hastings_Banda), a European-trained doctor who had been practicing in [Ghana](/Ghana). He was persuaded to return to [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland) in 1958 to lend his considerable intellect and charisma to the nationalist cause. [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) was swiftly elected president of the NAC and tirelessly worked to mobilize nationalist sentiment, a campaign that ultimately led to his imprisonment by colonial authorities in 1959. However, his incarceration only fueled the movement. He was released in 1960 and immediately tasked with helping to draft a new constitution for [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland), crucially including a clause that would grant Africans the majority representation in the colony's [Legislative Council](/Legislative_Council_of_Nyasaland) &#91;19&#93;. This was a decisive step towards self-rule.

### Hastings Kamuzu Banda era (1961–1993)

[Malawi's](/Malawi) first Prime Minister and later the inaugural [President](/President_of_Malawi), [Hastings Banda](/Hastings_Banda) (left), with [Tanzania's](/Tanzania) President [Julius Nyerere](/Julius_Nyerere) (right), captured in a moment of shared regional leadership.

The political landscape of [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland) irrevocably shifted in 1961 when [Banda's](/Hastings_Banda) [Malawi Congress Party](/Malawi_Congress_Party) (MCP) secured a decisive majority in the [Legislative Council elections](/Nyasaland_general_election,_1961), propelling [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) to the position of [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Malawi) in 1963. The contentious Federation was finally dissolved in 1963, paving the way for full sovereignty. On 6 July 1964, [Nyasaland](/Nyasaland) proudly declared its [independence](/Independence) from British rule, simultaneously renaming itself [Malawi](/Malawi). This momentous day is now annually commemorated as the nation's [Independence Day](/Public_holidays_in_Malawi), a cherished [public holiday](/Public_holidays_in_Malawi) &#91;29&#93;. Under a newly drafted constitution, [Malawi](/Malawi) formally transitioned into a republic in 1966, with [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) becoming its first president. The nascent government swiftly cemented the [MCP's](/Malawi_Congress_Party) power, formally establishing [Malawi](/Malawi) as a [one-party state](/One-party_state) where the [MCP](/Malawi_Congress_Party) was the sole legal political entity. Despite this shift, [Malawi](/Malawi) maintained its membership within the prestigious [Commonwealth](/Commonwealth_of_Nations).

In 1971, [Banda's](/Hastings_Banda) consolidation of power reached its zenith when he was controversially declared [president-for-life](/President-for-life), effectively entrenching his authoritarian rule. For nearly three decades, [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) presided over a rigidly [totalitarian](/Totalitarianism) regime, a period often credited with ensuring that [Malawi](/Malawi) remained free from armed conflict, albeit at the cost of widespread political repression &#91;30&#93;. During this era, opposition parties, such as the [Malawi Freedom Movement](/Malawi_Freedom_Movement) led by [Orton Chirwa](/Orton_Chirwa) and the [Socialist League of Malawi](/Socialist_League_of_Malawi), were compelled to operate in exile, their voices stifled within the country's borders. Despite the political constraints, [Malawi's](/Malawi) economy under [Banda's](/Hastings_Banda) presidency was frequently lauded as a remarkable example of how a poor, [landlocked](/Landlocked_country), and densely populated country, lacking significant mineral resources, could still achieve discernible progress in both its agricultural and industrial sectors &#91;31&#93;. One might argue that such "progress" often comes with a hefty price tag in terms of human liberty.

### Multi-party democracy (1993–present)

The relentless international and domestic pressure for increased [political freedom](/Political_freedom) eventually compelled [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) to concede to a national [referendum](/Malawian_democracy_referendum,_1993) in 1993. In this historic vote, the populace unequivocally chose to embrace a [multi-party democracy](/Multi-party_democracy), signaling a profound rejection of the long-standing single-party rule. By late 1993, a transitional presidential council was established, the highly criticized "life presidency" was abolished, and a [new constitution](/Constitution_of_Malawi) was promulgated, effectively dismantling the [MCP's](/Malawi_Congress_Party) entrenched authority &#91;30&#93;.

The year 1994 witnessed [Malawi's](/Malawi) [first multi-party elections](/Malawian_general_election,_1994), a truly democratic milestone, in which [Banda](/Hastings_Banda) was decisively defeated by [Bakili Muluzi](/Bakili_Muluzi), a figure who had previously served as the [MCP's](/Malawi_Congress_Party) Secretary General and a former minister in [Banda's](/Hastings_Banda) cabinet. [Muluzi](/Bakili_Muluzi) was re-elected in 1999 and continued his tenure until 2004, when [Bingu wa Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) was [elected](/Malawian_general_election,_2004) to the presidency &#91;32&#93;. Despite the political environment being characterized as "challenging" in 2009, the persistence of a [multi-party system](/Multi-party_system) in [Malawi](/Malawi) was affirmed &#91;33&#93;. Multiparty parliamentary and presidential [elections](/Malawian_general_election,_2009) were held for the fourth time in [Malawi](/Malawi) in May 2009, with President [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) securing re-election, a victory that was, however, shadowed by charges of election fraud from his political rivals &#91;34&#93;.

President [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) increasingly drew criticism for what some perceived as an autocratic leadership style and a growing disregard for human rights &#91;35&#93;. In July 2011, this simmering discontent boiled over into widespread [protests](/2011_Malawian_protests) across the nation. These demonstrations were fueled by a confluence of grievances, including soaring costs of living, deteriorating foreign relations, concerns over poor governance, and a critical shortage of foreign exchange reserves &#91;36&#93;. The government's response to these protests was tragically heavy-handed, resulting in the deaths of 18 individuals and leaving at least 44 others suffering from gunshot wounds &#91;37&#93;.

In a rather curious and short-lived alteration, the [Malawian flag](/Flag_of_Malawi) was modified in 2010. This change involved altering the three colored stripes and replacing the red rising sun with a full white sun. This revised flag existed for a brief period before the original colors of black, red, and green, along with the iconic red rising sun of the old flag, were thankfully restored in 2012. Some symbols, it seems, are best left untouched.

A significant political event occurred in April 2012 when President [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) died of a heart attack. What followed was a bizarre and rather unsettling 48-hour period during which his death was kept secret. This included an elaborate and ultimately futile attempt to fly his body to [South Africa](/South_Africa), where ambulance drivers, quite reasonably, refused to transport a corpse, citing a lack of appropriate licensing &#91;38&#93;. The charade only ended when the [South African](/South_Africa) government reportedly threatened to publicly reveal the information. Following this, the presidential title was constitutionally assumed by the then Vice-President, [Joyce Banda](/Joyce_Banda) &#91;39&#93;, who, to clarify, bore no relation to the former dictator [Hastings Banda](/Hastings_Banda) &#91;40&#93;.

In the [2014 Malawian general election](/2014_Malawian_general_election), [Joyce Banda](/Joyce_Banda) was unsuccessful in her bid for re-election, placing third. She was succeeded by [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika), the brother of the late ex-President [Bingu wa Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) &#91;41&#93;. The [2019 Malawian general election](/2019_Malawian_general_election) saw President [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika) narrowly re-elected. However, this victory was short-lived. In a landmark decision in February 2020, the [Malawi Constitutional Court](/Judiciary_of_Malawi) overturned the election result, citing widespread irregularities and undeniable fraud &#91;42&#93;. This ruling was subsequently upheld by the [Malawi Supreme Court](/Judiciary_of_Malawi) in May 2020, which then mandated a new election to be held on 2 July. This marked the very first instance in the country's history where an election result was successfully challenged through legal means &#91;43&#93; &#91;44&#93;. Opposition leader [Lazarus Chakwera](/Lazarus_Chakwera) emerged victorious in the ensuing [2020 Malawian presidential election](/2020_Malawian_presidential_election) and was duly sworn in as the new president of [Malawi](/Malawi) &#91;45&#93;. Yet, the political pendulum, ever swinging, returned to a familiar face. In September 2025, [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika) once again ascended to the presidency of [Malawi](/Malawi), winning the [2025 Malawian general election](/2025_Malawian_general_election) &#91;46&#93;. One might observe that Malawian politics possesses a certain... cyclical quality.

## Government and politics

* Main article: [Politics of Malawi](/Politics_of_Malawi)
* See also: [Elections in Malawi](/Elections_in_Malawi), [Judiciary of Malawi](/Judiciary_of_Malawi), and [Malawian Defence Force](/Malawian_Defence_Force)

[Malawi](/Malawi) functions as a [unitary presidential republic](/Presidential_system) under the leadership of President [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika), who, as noted, has proven remarkably resilient in the political arena. The foundational legal document governing the nation is its current constitution, which was formally enacted on 18 May 1995. The architecture of the [Malawian government](/Politics_of_Malawi), in adherence to the principle of [separation of powers](/Separation_of_powers), is structured into three distinct [branches](/Separation_of_powers): the [executive](/Executive_(government)), the [legislative](/Legislature), and the [judicial](/Judiciary).

The [executive branch](/Executive_(government)) is headed by the President, who simultaneously serves as both the [Head of State](/Head_of_State) and the [Head of Government](/Head_of_Government). The President and the First Vice President are elected jointly for a five-year term, ensuring a unified executive ticket. Additionally, the President holds the prerogative to appoint a second Vice President, though this individual must be drawn from a different political party, a measure presumably intended to foster broader political inclusion, or at least the appearance of it. The President is also solely responsible for appointing the members of the [Cabinet of Malawi](/Cabinet_of_Malawi), who may be selected from either within or outside the [legislature](/Legislature) &#91;20&#93;.

The National Assembly building, a prominent structure in [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe), stands as the physical embodiment of the legislative process.

The [legislative branch](/Legislature) is characterized by its [unicameral](/Unicameral) structure, comprising a [National Assembly](/National_Assembly_(Malawi)) consisting of 193 members. These representatives are elected every five years to serve the interests of their constituencies &#91;47&#93;. Intriguingly, while the [Malawian constitution](/Constitution_of_Malawi) makes provision for a [Senate](/Senate) of 80 seats, this upper chamber does not, in practice, exist. Should it ever be established, the [Senate](/Senate) is envisioned to provide dedicated representation for traditional leaders, a diverse array of geographic districts, and various special interest groups, including persons with disabilities, youth, and women. The [Malawi Congress Party](/Malawi_Congress_Party), currently led by [Lazarus Chakwera](/Lazarus_Chakwera), functions as the ruling party, while the [Democratic Progressive Party](/Democratic_Progressive_Party_(Malawi)) serves as the primary opposition force. [Suffrage](/Suffrage) is universal for all citizens aged 18 years and above. The central government's budget for the 2021/2022 fiscal year was reported at $2.4&#160;billion, a slight contraction from the $2.8&#160;billion allocated in the 2020/2021 financial year &#91;20&#93; &#91;48&#93;.

The independent [judicial branch](/Judiciary) of [Malawi](/Malawi) is largely modeled upon the principles of [English law](/English_law). Its hierarchy includes the highest court, the Supreme Court of Appeal, followed by a High Court that is further subdivided into three specialized sections: general, constitutional, and commercial. Below these, an Industrial Relations Court addresses labor disputes, and a network of Magistrates Courts, organized into five grades, handles a wide range of legal matters, including specialized Child Justice Courts &#91;49&#93;. The [judicial system](/Judiciary_of_Malawi) has undergone several modifications since the nation's [independence](/Independence) in 1964. Throughout its history, various combinations of conventional courts and [traditional courts](/Traditional_Courts_in_Malawi) have been employed, yielding mixed results in terms of effectiveness and susceptibility to corruption &#91;50&#93;.

[Malawi](/Malawi) is administratively structured into three distinct regions: the Northern, Central, and Southern regions &#91;51&#93;. These regions are further subdivided into 28&#160;[districts](/Districts_of_Malawi) &#91;52&#93;, which are then broken down into approximately 250&#160;traditional authorities and 110 administrative wards &#91;51&#93;. Local governance is overseen by regional administrators and district commissioners, who are appointed by the central government. A significant step towards democratic decentralization occurred on 21 November 2000, when local elections were held for the first time in the multi-party era, with the [United Democratic Front](/United_Democratic_Front) (UDF) party securing a substantial 70% of the available seats. A second round of constitutionally mandated local elections was initially scheduled for May 2005 but was unfortunately cancelled by the government &#91;20&#93;.

In a notable political maneuver in February 2005, President [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) severed ties with the [United Democratic Front](/United_Democratic_Front) and embarked on establishing his own political entity, the [Democratic Progressive Party](/Democratic_Progressive_Party_(Malawi)). This new party quickly garnered support, attracting reform-minded officials from other political factions and achieving successes in by-elections across the country in 2006. By 2008, President [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) had initiated a series of reforms aimed at tackling the nation's pervasive corruption problem, leading to criminal charges being brought against at least five senior [UDF](/United_Democratic_Front) party members &#91;53&#93;.

By 2012, [Malawi](/Malawi) had achieved a respectable 7th place among all countries in [sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub-Saharan_Africa) in the [Ibrahim Index of African Governance](/Ibrahim_Index_of_African_Governance), a comprehensive index that assesses governance across multiple variables. While the country's overall governance score surpassed the continental average, it lagged slightly behind the regional average for southern [Africa](/Africa). [Malawi](/Malawi) performed strongest in areas such as safety and rule of law, while its lowest scores were recorded in sustainable economic opportunity, ranking 47th on the continent for educational opportunities. Notably, [Malawi's](/Malawi) governance score demonstrated a positive improvement between 2000 and 2011 &#91;54&#93;. The nation conducted [elections](/2019_Malawian_general_election) in May 2019, which saw President [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika) secure re-election against formidable challengers including [Lazarus Chakwera](/Lazarus_Chakwera), [Atupele Muluzi](/Atupele_Muluzi), and [Saulos Chilima](/Saulos_Chilima) &#91;55&#93;. However, as previously mentioned, in 2020, the [Malawi Constitutional Court](/Judiciary_of_Malawi) annulled President [Peter Mutharika's](/Peter_Mutharika) narrow election victory from the previous year, citing widespread fraud and irregularities. Subsequently, opposition leader [Lazarus Chakwera](/Lazarus_Chakwera) triumphed in the [2020 Malawian presidential election](/2020_Malawian_presidential_election) and was installed as the new president &#91;56&#93;. Yet, the political narrative took another turn. In September 2025, a presidential election unfolded, culminating in a victory for former president [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika) of the [Democratic Progressive Party](/Democratic_Progressive_Party_(Malawi)). The incumbent president, [Lazarus Chakwera](/Lazarus_Chakwera) of the [Malawi Congress Party](/Malawi_Congress_Party), finished second, attributing his defeat to a confluence of challenging factors including the [Covid](/COVID-19) pandemic, devastating natural disasters such as drought and cyclones, and the significant economic downturn exacerbated by the war in [Ukraine](/Russo-Ukrainian_War). A truly predictable outcome, if one considers the inherent volatility of human memory and political cycles.

## Administrative divisions

A clickable map of [Malawi](/Malawi) vividly illustrating its 28 districts.

* Main articles: [Regions of Malawi](/Regions_of_Malawi) and [Districts of Malawi](/Districts_of_Malawi)

For administrative purposes, [Malawi](/Malawi) is systematically divided into 28 distinct districts, which are geographically organized within three overarching regions:

### [Central Region](/Central_Region,_Malawi)

This region encompasses nine crucial districts, forming the heart of the nation:
* 1&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Dedza District](/Dedza_District): Known for its mountainous terrain and historical rock art.
* 2&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Dowa District](/Dowa_District): A significant agricultural area, contributing to the country's food security.
* 3&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Kasungu District](/Kasungu_District): Home to [Kasungu National Park](/Kasungu_National_Park), offering diverse wildlife.
* 4&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Lilongwe District](/Lilongwe_District): The most populous district, containing the nation's capital, [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe).
* 5&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Mchinji District](/Mchinji_District): Bordering [Zambia](/Zambia), it plays a role in cross-border trade.
* 6&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Nkhotakhota District](/Nkhotakota_District): Historically significant as a slave trade route and located along [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi).
* 7&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Ntcheu District](/Ntcheu_District): Characterized by its rolling hills and agricultural activities.
* 8&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Ntchisi District](/Ntchisi_District): Features the [Ntchisi Forest Reserve](/Ntchisi_Forest_Reserve), an area of natural beauty.
* 9&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Salima District](/Salima_District): A popular tourist destination along the shores of [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi).

### [Northern Region](/Northern_Region,_Malawi)

The Northern Region comprises six districts, often noted for their scenic beauty and cultural heritage:
* 10&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Chitipa District](/Chitipa_District): Located in the far north, with borders to [Tanzania](/Tanzania) and [Zambia](/Zambia).
* 11&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Karonga District](/Karonga_District): An important lakeside district, known for its archaeological sites.
* 12&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Likoma District](/Likoma_District): Uniquely consists of islands within [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi), entirely surrounded by [Mozambican](/Mozambique) waters.
* 13&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Mzimba District](/Mzimba_District): The largest district by area, home to a significant [Tumbuka](/Tumbuka_people) population.
* 14&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Nkhata Bay District](/Nkhata_Bay_District): Famous for its vibrant market town and easy access to [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi).
* 15&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Rumphi District](/Rumphi_District): Features parts of [Nyika National Park](/Nyika_National_Park), a high-altitude plateau.

### [Southern Region](/Southern_Region,_Malawi)

The Southern Region, the most densely populated, is home to thirteen districts:
* 16&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Balaka District](/Balaka_District): A crossroads for transport and trade in the south.
* 17&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Blantyre District](/Blantyre_District): Contains the commercial capital, [Blantyre](/Blantyre), a bustling urban hub.
* 18&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Chikwawa District](/Chikhwawa_District): Situated in the lower [Shire Valley](/Shire_River), known for its hot climate.
* 19&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Chiradzulu District](/Chiradzulu_District): A small but densely populated district with intensive agriculture.
* 20&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Machinga District](/Machinga_District): Features diverse landscapes, including parts of [Liwonde National Park](/Liwonde_National_Park).
* 21&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Mangochi District](/Mangochi_District): A major tourist area along the southern end of [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi).
* 22&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Mulanje District](/Mulanje_District): Dominated by the imposing [Mulanje Massif](/Mulanje_Massif), a significant natural landmark.
* 23&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Mwanza District](/Mwanza_District): A smaller district known for its agricultural output.
* 24&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Nsanje District](/Nsanje_District): The southernmost district, bordering [Mozambique](/Mozambique) and the [Shire River](/Shire_River).
* 25&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Thyolo District](/Thyolo_District): Renowned for its extensive tea plantations.
* 26&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Phalombe District](/Phalombe_District): Located at the base of [Mount Mulanje](/Mulanje_Massif), susceptible to natural disasters.
* 27&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Zomba District](/Zomba_District): Home to the former colonial capital, [Zomba](/Zomba,_Malawi), and the scenic [Zomba Plateau](/Zomba_Plateau).
* 28&#160;&#8211;&#32;[Neno District](/Neno_District): One of the newer districts, carved out of [Mwanza](/Mwanza_District).

## Foreign relations

* Main article: [Foreign relations of Malawi](/Foreign_relations_of_Malawi)

Under the long tenure of former President [Hastings Banda](/Hastings_Banda), [Malawi](/Malawi) pursued a distinctly [pro-Western foreign policy](/Foreign_policy), a diplomatic orientation that largely persisted into early 2011. This stance fostered robust and amicable diplomatic relationships with numerous Western countries, establishing a foundation for international cooperation. The nation's subsequent transition from a [one-party state](/One-party_state) to a [multi-party democracy](/Multi-party_democracy) further solidified and strengthened its ties with the [United States](/United_States). This enduring partnership is evidenced by a significant number of [Malawian](/Malawi) students pursuing higher education in the [US](/United_States), and the active presence of various [US](/United_States) agencies within [Malawi](/Malawi), including the [Peace Corps](/Peace_Corps), the [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention](/Centers_for_Disease_Control_and_Prevention) (CDC), the [Department of Health and Human Services](/United_States_Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services), and the [Agency for International Development](/United_States_Agency_for_International_Development) (USAID), all contributing to development and capacity building.

A particularly sensitive aspect of [Malawi's](/Malawi) foreign policy history was its decision to maintain close [relations with South Africa](/Malawi%E2%80%93South_Africa_relations) throughout the [Apartheid](/Apartheid_in_South_Africa) era. This controversial stance inevitably strained [Malawi's](/Malawi) relationships with many other [African countries](/Africa), which viewed [Apartheid](/Apartheid_in_South_Africa) as an abhorrent system of racial oppression. However, following the collapse of [Apartheid](/Apartheid_in_South_Africa) in 1994, diplomatic relationships between [Malawi](/Malawi) and all other [African nations](/Africa) were re-established and maintained into 2011, reflecting a broader regional reconciliation. Despite this, [Malawi's](/Malawi) relationship with [Mozambique](/Mozambique) became notably strained in 2010. This tension was partly fueled by ongoing disputes over the utilization of the [Zambezi River](/Zambezi_River) and disagreements concerning an inter-country electrical grid, highlighting persistent regional challenges &#91;20&#93;. A significant shift in diplomatic alignment occurred in 2007 when [Malawi](/Malawi) established formal diplomatic ties with [China](/China). Since then, [Chinese investment](/Foreign_direct_investment) in the country has steadily escalated, bringing with it both opportunities and concerns, particularly regarding the treatment of local workers by [Chinese companies](/Chinese_company) and the competitive impact of [Chinese businesses](/Chinese_business) on local enterprises &#91;57&#93;.

2011 proved to be a particularly turbulent year for [Malawi's](/Malawi) foreign relations. A leaked document revealed sharp criticisms of President [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) by the British ambassador to [Malawi](/Malawi). In a swift and retaliatory move, [Mutharika](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) expelled the ambassador from the country. This diplomatic spat escalated further in July 2011 when the [UK](/United_Kingdom) announced the suspension of all budgetary aid to [Malawi](/Malawi), citing [Mutharika's](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) perceived lack of responsiveness to criticisms regarding his government's governance and economic mismanagement &#91;58&#93;. The [United States](/United_States) quickly followed suit on 26 July 2011, freezing a substantial US$350&#160;million grant. Their rationale included serious concerns about the government's suppression and intimidation of demonstrators and civic groups, as well as restrictions on press freedom and instances of police violence &#91;59&#93;. Such actions underscore the delicate balance between national sovereignty and international human rights obligations.

Locations of [Malawian diplomatic embassies or high commissions](/Malawian_diplomatic_missions) as of 2012 &#91;update&#93;.

Historically, [Malawi](/Malawi) has been regarded as a sanctuary for [refugees](/Refugee) fleeing conflicts and instability in other [African countries](/Africa), notably [Mozambique](/Mozambique) and [Rwanda](/Rwanda), with significant influxes dating back to 1985. While these waves of [refugees](/Refugee) have undeniably placed a strain on the [Malawian economy](/Economy_of_Malawi), they have also attracted substantial inflows of humanitarian and developmental aid from various international donors. Key contributors to [Malawi](/Malawi) include the [United States](/United_States), [Canada](/Canada), and [Germany](/Germany), alongside influential international institutions such as the [World Bank](/World_Bank), the [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund) (IMF), the [European Union](/European_Union), the [African Development Bank](/African_Development_Bank), and various [UN organizations](/United_Nations). [Malawi](/Malawi) maintains active membership in several prominent international organizations, including the [Commonwealth](/Commonwealth_of_Nations), the [United Nations](/United_Nations) and many of its specialized agencies, the IMF, the [World Bank](/World_Bank), the [African Union](/African_Union), and the [World Health Organization](/World_Health_Organization). The country holds the distinction of being the first in southern [Africa](/Africa) to receive specialized [peacekeeping](/Peacekeeping) training under the [African Crisis Response Initiative](/African_Contingency_Operations_Training_and_Assistance), highlighting its commitment to regional stability and security &#91;20&#93;.

According to the 2024 [Global Peace Index](/Global_Peace_Index), [Malawi](/Malawi) is ranked as the 79th most peaceful country in the world out of 163 nations &#91;60&#93;. A respectable showing, though peace, like freedom, is often a precarious state.

## Human rights

* See also: [Human rights in Malawi](/Human_rights_in_Malawi)

As of 2017 &#91;update&#93;, international observers continued to highlight persistent concerns across several critical areas of [human rights](/Human_rights_in_Malawi) within [Malawi](/Malawi). A particularly troubling issue was the documented use of excessive force by both police and other security forces, often with apparent impunity. Instances of mob violence were also occasionally reported, underscoring underlying social tensions. Furthermore, conditions within the country's prisons remained harsh and, in some cases, posed direct threats to the lives of inmates. Despite these challenges, the government was observed to be making some efforts to prosecute security force personnel found guilty of employing excessive force, indicating at least a partial commitment to accountability. Other legal issues of concern included limitations on [free speech](/Freedom_of_speech) and [freedom of the press](/Freedom_of_the_press), prolonged periods of pretrial detention, and instances of [arbitrary arrests](/Arbitrary_arrest) and detentions, which collectively undermine the rule of law. Corruption within government institutions was identified as a major systemic problem, an issue that persisted despite the efforts of the [Malawi Anti-Corruption Bureau](/Anti-Corruption_Bureau_(Malawi)) (ACB) to mitigate it. Corruption was also noted as a problem within the security forces themselves &#91;61&#93;. Tragically, [Malawi](/Malawi) historically faced one of the highest rates of [child marriage](/Child_marriage) globally &#91;62&#93;. In a positive legislative development in 2015, [Malawi](/Malawi) raised the legal age for marriage from 15 to 18, a crucial step towards protecting the rights and futures of young girls &#91;63&#93;.

Societal challenges that continued to plague the nation included widespread [violence against women](/Violence_against_women), instances of [human trafficking](/Human_trafficking), and the persistent problem of [child labour](/Child_labour). Additional concerns raised encompassed the lack of adequate legal protections for women against sexual abuse and harassment, an alarmingly high [maternal mortality](/Maternal_mortality) rate, and instances of abuse linked to accusations of [witchcraft](/Witchcraft) &#91;64&#93; &#91;65&#93; &#91;66&#93;. These issues collectively highlight the deep-seated social inequalities and vulnerabilities faced by certain segments of the population. As of 2010 &#91;update&#93;, [homosexuality](/LGBT_rights_in_Malawi) remained illegal in [Malawi](/Malawi). A high-profile case in that year saw a couple perceived as homosexual—a [man](/Man) and a [trans woman](/Trans_woman)—sentenced to extensive jail time upon conviction &#91;67&#93;. The convicted pair, each facing the maximum sentence of 14 years of hard labor, were, however, pardoned just two weeks later following direct intervention from [United Nations Secretary General](/United_Nations_Secretary_General) [Ban Ki-moon](/Ban_Ki-moon) &#91;68&#93;, demonstrating the power of international pressure. In a more progressive turn, in May 2012, then-President [Joyce Banda](/Joyce_Banda) publicly pledged to repeal the laws criminalizing [homosexuality](/Homosexuality) &#91;69&#93;. It was her successor, [Peter Mutharika](/Peter_Mutharika), who, in 2015, imposed a moratorium that effectively suspended the country's anti-gay laws, pending a further review of these statutes &#91;70&#93; &#91;71&#93;. A significant milestone for the [LGBT](/LGBT) community in [Malawi](/Malawi) occurred on 26 June 2021, when the country hosted its first ever [Pride parade](/Pride_parade) in [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe) &#91;70&#93;, a quiet, yet defiant, step towards greater inclusion. Progress, it seems, is a slow, winding path, often interrupted but rarely entirely abandoned.

## Geography

* Main article: [Geography of Malawi](/Geography_of_Malawi)

Mountains in Northern [Malawi](/Malawi) during the rainy season, a testament to the country's varied topography.

[Malawi](/Malawi) is a definitive [landlocked country](/Landlocked_country) in [southeastern Africa](/Southeast_Africa), its borders intimately shared with [Zambia](/Zambia) to the northwest, [Tanzania](/Tanzania) to the northeast, and [Mozambique](/Mozambique) to its south, southwest, and generally eastern flanks. It lies geographically between latitudes [9°](/9th_parallel_south) and [18°S](/18th_parallel_south), and longitudes [32°](/32nd_meridian_east) and [36°E](/36th_meridian_east). The colossal [Great Rift Valley](/East_African_Rift) carves its way directly through the country, running from north to south, a geological marvel that shapes much of the landscape. To the east of this dramatic valley lies [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi), also historically known as Lake [Nyasa](/Nyasa_(lake)), which astonishingly forms over three-quarters of [Malawi's](/Malawi) entire eastern boundary &#91;19&#93;. This immense body of water is sometimes affectionately referred to as the "Calendar Lake" due to a peculiar, almost poetic, coincidence: it stretches for approximately 365 miles (587&#160;km) in length and measures roughly 52 miles (84&#160;km) at its widest point &#91;72&#93;.

[Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi), a vast and deep freshwater sea.

Flowing from the southern extremity of [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) is the [Shire River](/Shire_River), which then meanders for 400 kilometers (250&#160;mi) further south before eventually merging with the mighty [Zambezi River](/Zambezi) in [Mozambique](/Mozambique). The surface of [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) itself is situated at an elevation of 457 meters (1,500&#160;ft) above sea level. However, its depths are truly profound, reaching a maximum recorded depth of 701 meters (2,300&#160;ft). This means that at certain points, the lake bottom plunges to more than 213 meters (700&#160;ft) *below* sea level &#91;73&#93;, making it one of the deepest lakes in the world, a true geological anomaly.

In the more mountainous sections of [Malawi](/Malawi) that flank the [Rift Valley](/East_African_Rift), plateaus generally ascend to elevations ranging from 914 to 1,219 meters (3,000 to 4,000&#160;ft) above sea level. In the north, some of these impressive formations soar even higher, reaching up to 2,438 meters (8,000&#160;ft). South of [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) lies the [Shire Highlands](/Shire_Highlands), an area characterized by gently rolling terrain at an average elevation of approximately 914 meters (3,000&#160;ft) above sea level. Within this region, the majestic [Zomba](/Zomba,_Malawi) and [Mulanje](/Mulanje_Massif) mountain peaks stand as prominent landmarks, rising to impressive heights of 2,134 and 3,048 meters (7,000 and 10,000&#160;ft) respectively &#91;19&#93;.

[Malawi's](/Malawi) official capital is [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe), a city that serves as its political and administrative center. Its bustling commercial hub, however, is [Blantyre](/Blantyre), a metropolitan area boasting a population exceeding 500,000&#160;people &#91;19&#93;. The country is also a custodian of significant cultural and natural heritage, proudly featuring two sites inscribed on the prestigious [UNESCO World Heritage List](/UNESCO_World_Heritage_List). The [Lake Malawi National Park](/Lake_Malawi_National_Park) was the first to receive this esteemed designation in 1984, recognized for its exceptional biodiversity and unique cichlid fish species. The [Chongoni Rock Art Area](/Chongoni_Rock_Art_Area) followed, listed in 2006, celebrated for its ancient rock paintings that offer invaluable insights into the region's historical human settlements &#91;74&#93;.

The [climate of Malawi](/Climate_of_Malawi) exhibits distinct regional variations. In the low-lying southern areas of the country, the climate is typically hot, often intensely so. Conversely, the northern highlands enjoy a more temperate climate, moderated by their higher altitude, which effectively counteracts what would otherwise be a perpetually equatorial environment. The period between November and April is characterized by warm temperatures accompanied by equatorial rains and frequent thunderstorms. These storms reach their peak intensity and severity in late March. Following March, the rainfall rapidly subsides, and from May to September, wet mists frequently drift from the highlands into the plateaus, with these months experiencing almost negligible rainfall &#91;19&#93;. A predictable cycle, if nothing else.

## Flora and fauna

* Main article: [Wildlife of Malawi](/Wildlife_of_Malawi)

An elephant, a magnificent resident of the [Majete Wildlife Reserve](/Majete_Wildlife_Reserve), a testament to [Malawi's](/Malawi) conservation efforts.

The vibrant [animal life indigenous to Malawi](/List_of_mammals_of_Malawi) is remarkably diverse, a testament to its varied ecosystems. This includes a robust population of [mammals](/List_of_mammals_of_Malawi) such as the majestic elephants, ponderous hippos, graceful antelopes, formidable buffaloes, the elusive big cats (lions, leopards), playful monkeys, the critically endangered rhinos, and a myriad of bats. The country is also a haven for a great variety of [birds](/List_of_birds_of_Malawi), encompassing powerful birds of prey, colorful parrots, swift falcons, numerous waterfowl and large waders, as well as nocturnal owls and melodious songbirds. [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) itself is, without exaggeration, often described as possessing one of the richest lake fish faunas in the entire world, a veritable underwater Eden. This singular lake alone is home to an astonishing array of biodiversity, supporting some 200 species of mammals, 650 species of birds, over 30 species of mollusks, and more than 5,500 species of plants &#91;75&#93;. A staggering concentration of life, indeed.

Geographically, seven distinct terrestrial [ecoregions](/Ecoregion) intersect and define [Malawi's](/Malawi) natural borders. These include the [Central Zambezian miombo woodlands](/Central_Zambezian_miombo_woodlands), the [Eastern miombo woodlands](/Eastern_miombo_woodlands), the [Southern miombo woodlands](/Southern_miombo_woodlands), the [Zambezian and mopane woodlands](/Zambezian_and_mopane_woodlands), and the [Zambezian flooded grasslands](/Zambezian_flooded_grasslands). Additionally, two montane forest-grassland mosaics contribute to the ecological richness: the [South Malawi montane forest-grassland mosaic](/South_Malawi_montane_forest-grassland_mosaic) and the [Southern Rift montane forest-grassland mosaic](/Southern_Rift_montane_forest-grassland_mosaic) &#91;76&#93;. To safeguard this precious natural heritage, [Malawi](/Malawi) has established five [national parks](/Category:National_parks_of_Malawi), four dedicated [wildlife and game reserves](/Category:Protected_areas_of_Malawi), and two other designated [protected areas](/Category:Protected_areas_of_Malawi) &#91;77&#93;. In 2019, the country recorded a [Forest Landscape Integrity Index](/Forest_Landscape_Integrity_Index) mean score of 5.74/10, placing it 96th globally out of 172 countries &#91;78&#93;, indicating that while significant natural areas remain, they face ongoing pressures.

## Economy

* Main article: [Economy of Malawi](/Economy_of_Malawi)
* See also: [Malawian food crisis](/Malawian_food_crisis) and [List of companies based in Malawi](/List_of_companies_based_in_Malawi)

A vibrant crafts market in [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe), showcasing local artistry and enterprise.

[Malawi](/Malawi) holds the unenviable distinction of being among the world's [least developed countries](/Least_developed_countries). A staggering approximately 85% of its population resides in rural areas, their livelihoods intrinsically tied to the land. The national [economy](/Economy_of_Malawi) is overwhelmingly anchored in [agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Malawi), a sector that, while employing the vast majority, accounts for more than one-third of the country's [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) and a dominant 90% of its export revenues. Historically, the [economy](/Economy_of_Malawi) has been heavily reliant on substantial economic aid and financial support from international bodies such as the [World Bank](/World_Bank), the [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund) (IMF), and various donor countries &#91;52&#93;. Despite these challenges, [Malawi](/Malawi) was ranked as the 119th safest investment destination globally in the March 2011 Euromoney Country Risk rankings &#91;79&#93;, suggesting some underlying, if nascent, stability. The [Malawian government](/Politics_of_Malawi) faces a formidable array of challenges, including the imperative to cultivate a more robust market economy, enhance environmental protection measures, effectively address the rapidly escalating [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS) epidemic, significantly improve its education system, and ultimately satisfy its foreign donors to achieve a greater degree of financial independence. A rather lengthy to-do list, one might observe.

In a significant setback for the nation, the IMF suspended its aid disbursements in December 2000, citing serious concerns regarding pervasive corruption. Numerous individual donors subsequently followed suit, resulting in a precipitous almost 80% decline in [Malawi's](/Malawi) development budget &#91;53&#93;. However, by 2005, the tide had turned somewhat, with [Malawi](/Malawi) becoming the recipient of over US$575&#160;million in aid, a testament to renewed international confidence, or perhaps just a desperate need for intervention. Many economic analysts firmly believe that sustainable economic progress for [Malawi](/Malawi) is inextricably linked to its ability to effectively manage and control its rapid population growth &#91;80&#93;. A rather revealing incident occurred in 2009: the government's acquisition of a private presidential jet was almost immediately followed by a nationwide fuel shortage. While officially attributed to logistical problems, it was far more likely the direct consequence of the hard currency shortage exacerbated by the extravagant jet purchase &#91;81&#93; &#91;82&#93; &#91;83&#93;. One does wonder about priorities.

Furthermore, [Malawi](/Malawi) has encountered several economic setbacks, including a diminished capacity to pay for crucial imports due to a general scarcity of foreign exchange. This situation was compounded by a 23% decline in investment in 2009. The country faces numerous formidable investment barriers that the government has, thus far, struggled to adequately address. These include prohibitively high service costs and severely inadequate infrastructure, particularly in critical sectors such as power, water, and telecommunications. As of 2017 &#91;update&#93;, [Malawi](/Malawi) was estimated to have a [purchasing power parity](/Purchasing_power_parity) (PPP) of $22.42&#160;billion, with a rather modest per capita [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) of $1200, and an inflation rate estimated at 12.2% in the same year &#91;52&#93;.

Breaking down the economic sectors, [agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Malawi) contributes approximately 35% of the [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product), while industry accounts for 19%, leaving the remaining 46% to the [services sector](/Service_(economics)) &#91;33&#93;. Despite experiencing impressive economic growth rates, estimated at 9.7% in 2008, and strong growth projections from the [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund) for 2009 &#91;84&#93;, [Malawi](/Malawi) still contends with one of the lowest per capita incomes globally &#91;53&#93;. Encouragingly, the [poverty rate](/Poverty_rate) in [Malawi](/Malawi) has shown a decreasing trend, largely thanks to the concerted efforts of the government and various supporting organizations. The percentage of people living below the poverty line decreased from 54% in 1990 to 40% in 2006, and the proportion of the "ultra-poor" saw a reduction from 24% in 1990 to 15% in 2007 &#91;85&#93;. However, such progress is fragile. In January 2015, southern [Malawi](/Malawi) was devastated by severe floods. These catastrophic floods impacted over a million people across the country, with approximately 336,000 individuals displaced from their homes, according to [UNICEF](/UNICEF). The human cost was immense, with over 100 lives lost and an estimated 64,000 hectares of vital cropland tragically washed away &#91;86&#93;, demonstrating how quickly natural disasters can erase hard-won gains.

### Agriculture and industry

* Main article: [Agriculture in Malawi](/Agriculture_in_Malawi)

Harvesting [groundnuts](/Bambara_groundnut) at an agricultural research station in [Malawi](/Malawi), a vital activity for the nation's food security.

The [economy of Malawi](/Economy_of_Malawi) is, at its core, predominantly agricultural. Over 80% of the population is engaged in [subsistence farming](/Subsistence_agriculture), a fundamental activity that, despite its widespread practice, contributed only 27% to the national [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) in 2013. In contrast, the [services sector](/Services_sector) accounts for a more substantial portion, exceeding half of the [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) (54%), while manufacturing contributes 11%, and other industries, including nascent natural uranium mining, make up 8% &#91;87&#93; &#91;88&#93; &#91;89&#93;. Notably, [Malawi](/Malawi) invests a larger share of its [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) in [agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Malawi) (28%) than any other [African country](/Africa), underscoring its profound reliance on this sector.

Starting in 2006, the country initiated a strategic move to blend unleaded petrol with 10% [ethanol](/Ethanol), which is produced domestically at two plants. This initiative was designed to lessen the nation's dependence on imported fuel, a sensible step towards energy independence. In the same year, in response to persistently low agricultural harvests and the threat of food insecurity, [Malawi](/Malawi) launched a comprehensive program of [fertilizer](/Fertilizer) subsidies, known as the Fertiliser Input Subsidy Programme (FISP). This program, championed by the country's president at the time, was reportedly instrumental in transforming [Malawi](/Malawi) into a net exporter of food to neighboring countries &#91;90&#93;, a remarkable achievement. However, the FISP regrettably concluded with President [Mutharika's](/Bingu_wa_Mutharika) death. In 2020, the program was revitalized and replaced with the Affordable Inputs Program (AIP), which expanded the subsidy on maize seed and [fertilizer](/Fertilizer) to include [sorghum](/Sorghum) and rice seed, demonstrating an ongoing commitment to agricultural support &#91;91&#93;.

The primary agricultural products cultivated in [Malawi](/Malawi) are diverse and crucial to its economy, including [tobacco](/Tobacco), [sugarcane](/Sugarcane), [cotton](/Gossypium), [tea](/Camellia_sinensis), [corn](/Maize) (maize), potatoes, sorghum, as well as livestock such as cattle and goats. The nation's main industries revolve around the processing of these agricultural outputs, particularly tobacco, tea, and sugar. Other significant industrial activities include [sawmill](/Sawmill) products, cement manufacturing, and the production of various [consumer goods](/Final_good). The industrial production growth rate was estimated at a robust 10% in 2009. Despite its reliance on natural resources, the country makes no significant use of natural gas. As of 2008 &#91;update&#93;, [Malawi](/Malawi) neither imports nor exports electricity, but remains entirely dependent on imported petroleum, with no domestic production of crude oil &#91;52&#93;. In a forward-thinking initiative, [Malawi](/Malawi) began testing cars powered solely by [ethanol](/Ethanol) in 2008, and the country continues to expand its use of [ethanol](/Ethanol) as an alternative fuel source &#91;92&#93;.

Children attending a [farmer](/Farmer) meeting in Nalifu village, [Mulanje](/Mulanje), highlighting the importance of agricultural knowledge transfer.

As of 2009, [Malawi](/Malawi) exported an estimated US$945 million in goods annually. However, the nation's economic stability is frequently threatened by fluctuations in global commodity prices. The world prices for [tobacco](/Tobacco), a cornerstone of [Malawi's](/Malawi) exports, have seen a decline, and the international community has intensified pressure to limit [tobacco](/Tobacco) production due to health concerns. Paradoxically, [Malawi's](/Malawi) dependence on [tobacco](/Tobacco) has actually increased, with the product's contribution to export revenues climbing from 53% to a staggering 70% between 2007 and 2008. The country also relies heavily on tea, tobacco, sugar, and coffee, which collectively account for over 90% of [Malawi's](/Malawi) total export revenue &#91;52&#93; &#91;53&#93;.

In light of rising production costs and a decline in sales prices for traditional crops, [Malawi](/Malawi) is actively encouraging its farmers to diversify away from [tobacco](/Tobacco) towards more profitable alternatives, including spices such as [paprika](/Paprika). This strategic shift away from [tobacco](/Tobacco) is further propelled by anticipated moves from the [World Health Organization](/World_Health_Organization) (WHO) to restrict the particular type of [tobacco](/Tobacco) that [Malawi](/Malawi) primarily produces, [burley leaf](/Burley_(tobacco)), which is deemed more detrimental to human health than other [tobacco products](/Tobacco_product). [India hemp](/Hemp) has also been proposed as a potential alternative crop. However, arguments have been raised that its cultivation could inadvertently lead to an increase in crime within the country, primarily due to its striking resemblance to varieties of [cannabis](/Cannabis_(drug)) used as a [recreational drug](/Recreational_drug), making it challenging to distinguish between the two types &#91;93&#93;. Indeed, the cultivation of [Malawian cannabis](/Malawi_Gold), famously known as "[Malawi Gold](/Malawi_Gold)," as a recreational drug has seen a significant increase &#91;94&#93;. According to a recent [World Bank](/World_Bank) report, [Malawi](/Malawi) is known for growing "the best and finest" [cannabis](/Cannabis_(drug)) in the world for [recreational drug use](/Recreational_drug_use), and the cultivation and sales of this crop may unfortunately contribute to corruption within the police force &#91;95&#93;. A fine line, it seems, between economic opportunity and illicit activity.

[GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) in [Southern African Development Community](/Southern_African_Development_Community) countries by economic sector, 2013 or closest year &#91;96&#93;.

Other significant exported goods from [Malawi](/Malawi) include cotton, peanuts, wood products, and [apparel](/Clothing). The primary destination markets for the country's exports are [South Africa](/South_Africa), [Germany](/Germany), [Egypt](/Egypt), [Zimbabwe](/Zimbabwe), the [United States](/United_States), [Russia](/Russia), and the [Netherlands](/Netherlands). Conversely, [Malawi](/Malawi) currently imports an estimated US$1.625&#160;billion in goods annually. The main imported commodities are essential items such as food, petroleum products, various [consumer goods](/Final_good), and transportation equipment. The principal countries from which [Malawi](/Malawi) imports are [South Africa](/South_Africa), [India](/India), [Zambia](/Zambia), [Tanzania](/Tanzania), the [US](/United_States), and [China](/China) &#91;52&#93;.

The fragility of [Malawi's](/Malawi) agricultural sector was starkly exposed in 2016 when the country was severely impacted by a widespread drought. This was compounded in January 2017, when the country reported a devastating outbreak of [armyworms](/African_armyworm) around [Zomba](/Zomba,_Malawi). This highly destructive moth species is notorious for its ability to wipe out entire fields of [corn](/Maize), which is the staple grain for the majority of [Malawian](/Malawi) residents &#91;97&#93;. By 14 January 2017, the agriculture minister, [George Chaponda](/George_Chaponda), confirmed that 2,000 hectares of vital crops had already been destroyed, with the infestation rapidly spreading to nine of the country's twenty-eight districts &#91;98&#93;. A constant battle against the elements, it seems.

## Infrastructure

* Main articles: [Transport in Malawi](/Transport_in_Malawi), [Rail transport in Malawi](/Rail_transport_in_Malawi), and [Communications in Malawi](/Communications_in_Malawi)

The M1 road connecting [Blantyre](/Blantyre) and [Lilongwe](/Lilongwe), a crucial artery for national transport.

As of 2012 &#91;update&#93;, [Malawi](/Malawi) possessed a total of 31&#160;[airports](/Airport). Of these, seven featured paved runways, including two designated as [international airports](/International_airport), facilitating global connectivity. The remaining 24 airports operated with unpaved runways, serving more localized air travel needs. In terms of [railways](/Rail_transport_in_Malawi), as of 2008 &#91;update&#93;, the country maintained 797 kilometers (495&#160;mi) of tracks, all of which were [narrow-gauge](/Narrow-gauge). The [roadways](/Roadway) network, as of 2003, spanned an extensive 24,866 kilometers (15,451&#160;mi), though conditions varied significantly; 6,956 kilometers (4,322&#160;mi) were paved, offering smoother transit, while 8,495 kilometers (5,279&#160;mi) remained unpaved, presenting more challenging travel conditions. Additionally, [Malawi](/Malawi) benefits from 700 kilometers (430&#160;mi) of navigable [waterways](/Waterway) on [Lake Malawi](/Lake_Malawi) and along the [Shire River](/Shire_River), providing essential transport routes for both goods and people &#91;52&#93;.

The telecommunications landscape in [Malawi](/Malawi) has seen significant growth. As of 2022 &#91;update&#93;, there were an impressive 10.23&#160;million mobile phone connections throughout the country, indicating a high penetration rate for cellular services. Internet access, while still developing, also showed progress, with 4.03 million users reported in 2022 &#91;9&#93;. In the realm of broadcasting, as of 2022 &#91;update&#93;, [Malawi](/Malawi) operated one government-run radio station, the [Malawi Broadcasting Corporation](/Malawi_Broadcasting_Corporation), alongside approximately a dozen more owned by private enterprises, offering a diverse range of auditory content. Radio, television, and postal services within [Malawi](/Malawi) are all subject to regulation by the [Malawi Communications Regulatory Authority](/Malawi_Communications_Regulatory_Authority) (MACRA) &#91;99&#93; &#91;100&#93;, ensuring a degree of order in the airwaves. Historically, [Malawi's](/Malawi) telecommunications system was often cited as among the poorest in [Africa](/Africa). However, conditions have demonstrably improved, with a notable increase of 130,000 landline telephones connected between 2000 and 2007. Despite this progress, telephone access remains significantly more concentrated in urban areas, with less than a quarter of all landlines serving rural populations &#91;101&#93;. By 2016, the country boasted 20 television stations operating on its digital network, MDBNL &#91;52&#93;, further expanding media access for its citizens.

## Science and technology

* Main article: [Science and technology in Malawi](/Science_and_technology_in_Malawi)

### Research trends

Scientific publication trends in the most productive [SADC](/Southern_African_Development_Community) countries, 2005–2014 &#91;96&#93;. A chart revealing the cold, hard data of intellectual output.

In 2010, [Malawi](/Malawi) demonstrated a notable commitment to knowledge generation, dedicating 1.06% of its [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) to [research and development](/Research_and_development), according to a survey conducted by the Department of Science and Technology. This figure represents one of the highest ratios observed across [Africa](/Africa), equating to $7.8 per researcher (in current purchasing parity dollars) &#91;87&#93; &#91;88&#93;.

By 2014, [Malawian scientists](/Malawian_scientist) had achieved the third-largest output in [Southern Africa](/Southern_Africa) in terms of articles cataloged in international journals. They published 322 articles in [Thomson Reuters](/Thomson_Reuters)' Web of Science that year, nearly tripling the number recorded in 2005 (116). Only [South Africa](/South_Africa) (9,309) and [Tanzania](/Tanzania) (770) surpassed [Malawi's](/Malawi) publication volume within [Southern Africa](/Southern_Africa). Furthermore, [Malawian scientists](/Malawian_scientist) exhibit a particularly impressive rate of publication in mainstream journals—relative to their country's [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product)—surpassing any other nation of comparable population size, with 19 publications per million inhabitants cataloged in international journals in 2014. This compares favorably to the average for [sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub-Saharan_Africa), which stands at 20 publications per million inhabitants &#91;87&#93; &#91;88&#93;. [Malawi](/Malawi) was ranked 125th in the [Global Innovation Index](/Global_Innovation_Index) in 2025 &#91;102&#93; &#91;103&#93;, suggesting that while research output is strong, converting it into broader innovation remains a challenge.

### Policy framework

[Malawi's](/Malawi) initial [science and technology policy](/Science_and_technology_in_Malawi) was formulated in 1991 and subsequently revised in 2002. The [National Science and Technology Policy of 2002](/National_Science_and_Technology_Policy_of_2002) was ambitious, envisioning the establishment of a [National Commission for Science and Technology](/National_Commission_for_Science_and_Technology) (NCST). This commission was intended to serve as a key advisory body to the government and other stakeholders on matters pertaining to science and technology-led development. Although the [Science and Technology Act of 2003](/Science_and_Technology_Act_of_2003) legally provided for the creation of this commission, it only became fully operational in 2011, with its secretariat formed from the merger of the Department of Science and Technology and the National Research Council. The same 2003 Act also mandated the establishment of a Science and Technology Fund, designed to finance crucial research and studies through government grants and loans. However, as of 2014 &#91;update&#93;, this fund had not yet become operational, a rather typical bureaucratic delay. The Secretariat of the [National Commission for Science and Technology](/National_Commission_for_Science_and_Technology) has since undertaken a review of the [Strategic Plan for Science, Technology, and Innovation](/Strategic_Plan_for_Science,_Technology,_and_Innovation) (2011–2015), but as of early 2015, the revised policy was still awaiting Cabinet approval &#91;87&#93; &#91;88&#93;. One might surmise that the pace of policy implementation is less than stellar.

In 2012, the majority of foreign investments flowing into [Malawi](/Malawi) were directed towards infrastructure projects (62%) and the energy sector (33%), highlighting critical areas for development. To further stimulate foreign direct investment, the government has introduced a series of fiscal incentives, including various tax breaks. In 2013, the [Malawi Investment and Trade Centre](/Malawi_Investment_and_Trade_Centre) compiled an investment portfolio encompassing 20 companies, actively seeking to attract external capital. In the same year, the government adopted a [National Export Strategy](/National_Export_Strategy) with the explicit goal of diversifying the country's export base, moving beyond its traditional agricultural commodities. This strategy aims to establish production facilities for a broad spectrum of products within three carefully selected clusters: oilseed products, sugar cane products, and manufacturing &#91;87&#93; &#91;88&#93;. A clear attempt to broaden its economic horizons, which is, frankly, long overdue.

