[Malawi's](/Malawi) population is a rich tapestry woven from numerous [ethnic groups](/Ethnic_group), primarily comprising the indigenous [Chewa](/Chewa_people), [Tumbuka](/Tumbuka_people), [Yao](/Yao_(ethnic_group_in_Africa)), [Lomwe](/Lomwe_people), [Sena](/Sena_people), [Tonga](/Tonga_people_of_Malawi), [Ngoni](/Ngoni_people), and [Ngonde](/Ngonde) communities. These groups represent the historical and cultural bedrock of the nation, each contributing distinct traditions, languages, and social structures. In addition to these dominant indigenous groups, [Malawi](/Malawi) also hosts smaller but significant populations of [Chinese](/Chinese_people_in_Malawi) and [Europeans](/White_Africans_of_European_ancestry), whose presence reflects historical migratory patterns, colonial legacies, and modern economic ties. This blend of cultures and ancestries contributes to the unique social fabric of [Malawi](/Malawi), creating a diverse and dynamic society.

