The linguistic landscape of [Malawi](/Malawi) is both singular and diverse. The country's only official language, a legacy of its colonial past, is [English](/English_language) &#91;112&#93;. However, the nation does not formally declare a single national language within its constitution, opting instead to recognize several major indigenous languages as regional tongues. This pragmatic approach acknowledges the rich linguistic heritage of its people.

A [Malawi](/Malawi) health passport, clearly illustrating the three major languages most commonly used in the country: [English](/English_language) (red dot), [Chichewa](/Chewa_language) (blue dot), and [Chitumbuka](/Tumbuka_language) (green dot).

Among these regionally recognized languages are [Chichewa](/Chewa_language), spoken by a significant 42.5% of the population, [Chitumbuka](/Tumbuka_language), used by 31.2%, and [Chiyao](/Yao_language), which accounts for 13.7% of speakers &#91;52&#93;. Beyond these prominent languages, several other [native languages](/Native_language) contribute to [Malawi's](/Malawi) linguistic mosaic. These include [Malawian Lomwe](/Malawi_Lomwe_language), spoken by an estimated 250,000 individuals primarily in the southeastern parts of the country; [Kokola](/Kokola), with approximately 200,000 speakers also in the southeast; [Lambya](/Lambya_people), spoken by around 45,000 people in the northwestern tip; [Ndali](/Ndali_language), used by roughly 70,000; [Nyakyusa-Ngonde](/Nyakyusa_language), with approximately 300,000 speakers concentrated in northern [Malawi](/Malawi); [Malawian Sena](/Sena_language), spoken by about 270,000 people in southern [Malawi](/Malawi); and [Tonga](/Tonga_(Nyasa)_language), which has around 170,000 speakers in the [Nkhata Bay District](/Nkhata_Bay_District) in the north &#91;113&#93;.

In the realm of education, all students enrolled in public elementary schools across [Malawi](/Malawi) receive their instruction in [Chichewa](/Chewa_language), despite it not being formally designated as the official national language. Conversely, students attending private elementary schools are typically instructed in [English](/English_language), particularly if these institutions adhere to either the American or British curricula &#91;114&#93;. This dual system reflects the ongoing interplay between indigenous linguistic heritage and the global influence of [English](/English_language) in education.

### Religion

* Further information: [Religion in Malawi](/Religion_in_Malawi), [Christianity in Malawi](/Christianity_in_Malawi), [Roman Catholicism in Malawi](/Roman_Catholicism_in_Malawi), [Islam in Malawi](/Islam_in_Malawi), [Hinduism in Malawi](/Hinduism_in_Malawi), and [Baháʼí Faith in Malawi](/Bah%C3%A1%CA%BC%C3%AD_Faith_in_Malawi)

Religion in [Malawi](/Malawi) (2018) &#91;115&#93;

* [Christianity](/Christianity) (77.3%)
* [Islam](/Islam) (13.8%)
* Traditional (1.10%)
* Other or none (7.80%)

A Mission Church in [Livingstonia](/Livingstonia,_Malawi), a historical testament to the arrival and spread of [Christianity](/Christianity) in the region.

[Malawi](/Malawi) is predominantly a [Christian](/Christianity) country, with a substantial [Muslim](/Islam) minority contributing significantly to its religious diversity. Government surveys indicate that a commanding 87% of the country's population identifies as [Christian](/Christianity), while a notable 11.6% adheres to [Islam](/Islam) &#91;2&#93;. Among the various [Christian groups](/Christian_denomination) in [Malawi](/Malawi), the [Roman Catholic Church](/Roman_Catholic_Church_in_Malawi) is the largest single denomination, claiming 19% of Malawians as adherents. Following closely is the [Church of Central Africa Presbyterian](/Church_of_Central_Africa_Presbyterian) (CCAP), to which 18% of the population belongs &#91;2&#93;. The CCAP stands as the largest [Protestant denomination](/Protestantism) in [Malawi](/Malawi), boasting an impressive 1.3&#160;million members. Additionally, there are smaller [Presbyterian](/Presbyterianism) denominations such as the [Reformed Presbyterian Church of Malawi](/Reformed_Presbyterian_Church_of_Malawi) and the [Evangelical Presbyterian Church of Malawi](/Evangelical_Presbyterian_Church_of_Malawi). The religious landscape also includes smaller numbers of [Anglicans](/Anglicanism), [Baptists](/Baptists), evangelicals, [Seventh-day Adventists](/Seventh-day_Adventist_Church), and [Lutherans](/Lutheran_Church_of_Central_Africa) &#91;116&#93;.

The majority of the [Muslim population](/Islam_in_Malawi) in [Malawi](/Malawi) identifies as [Sunni](/Sunni), belonging to either the [Qadriya](/Qadriya) or Sukkutu groups &#91;117&#93;, reflecting specific Sufi orders and local interpretations of [Islam](/Islam). Other religious groups present within the country include [Jehovah's Witnesses](/Jehovah%27s_Witnesses), numbering over 100,000 adherents &#91;118&#93;; [The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints](/The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Saints), which reported over 2,000 members by the end of 2015 &#91;119&#93;; followers of the [Rastafari movement](/Rastafari_movement); [Hindus](/Hindu); and [Baháʼís](/Bah%C3%A1%CA%BC%C3%AD_Faith), who constitute approximately 0.2% of the population &#91;120&#93;. [Atheists](/Atheism) make up around 4% of the population, although this figure may also encompass individuals who practice traditional [African religions](/Traditional_African_religions) that do not necessarily adhere to the concept of specific deities &#91;121&#93;. This rich religious tapestry underscores the freedom of belief, or lack thereof, within the nation.

### Health

* Main article: [Healthcare in Malawi](/Healthcare_in_Malawi)

[Malawi's](/Malawi) [healthcare system](/Healthcare_in_Malawi) is structured to serve its population through a combination of central hospitals, regional facilities, and a growing private sector. The public health sector endeavors to offer free health services and essential medicines, aiming to provide accessible care to all citizens. In contrast, various [non-government organizations](/Non-government_organizations) (NGOs) and private doctors operate on a fee-for-service basis, providing additional options for those who can afford them. Health insurance schemes have also been progressively established since 2000, seeking to broaden access to care and mitigate financial burdens. The country even boasts a nascent [pharmaceutical manufacturing](/Pharmaceutical_manufacturing) industry, comprising four privately owned pharmaceutical companies &#91;123&#93;, a crucial step towards self-sufficiency in medicine production. Among the major health facilities in the country are the Blantyre Adventist Hospital, Mwaiwathu Private Hospital, and Kamuzu Central Hospitals &#91;124&#93;, serving as critical healthcare hubs.

Despite these efforts, [Malawi](/Malawi) continues to grapple with significant health challenges. [Infant mortality](/Infant_mortality) rates remain high, and the overall [life expectancy](/Life_expectancy) at birth is a concerning 50.03&#160;years. The legal framework surrounding [abortion](/Abortion_in_Malawi) is restrictive, with the procedure being illegal in [Malawi](/Malawi) except in cases where it is deemed necessary to save the mother's life &#91;125&#93;. The Penal Code imposes severe penalties, punishing women who seek illegal or clinical abortions with up to 7 years in prison, while those who perform such abortions face a harsher sentence of 14 years &#91;126&#93;.

The country also faces a high adult prevalence rate of [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS), a pervasive public health crisis. In 2022, an estimated 1,006,633 people were living with the disease, with 94% of these being adults aged over 15. Tragically, approximately 11,931 deaths were attributed to [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS) in the same year &#91;127&#93;, and a staggering 440,000 children had been orphaned due to the disease by 2022 &#91;128&#93;. The relentless spread of infection sees approximately 250 new individuals infected each day, and a grim statistic reveals that at least 70% of [Malawi's](/Malawi) hospital beds are occupied by [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS) patients. The economic toll is also immense, with an estimated 5.8% of the vital farm labor force succumbing to the disease. The government itself incurs significant costs, spending over $120,000 annually on funerals for civil servants who die from [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS) &#91;53&#93;.

Beyond [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS), there is a very high degree of risk for various infectious diseases, including bacterial and protozoal [diarrhoea](/Diarrhoea), [hepatitis A](/Hepatitis_A), [typhoid fever](/Typhoid_fever), [malaria](/Malaria), [plague](/Plague_(disease)), [schistosomiasis](/Schistosomiasis), and [rabies](/Rabies) &#91;52&#93;. While [Malawi](/Malawi) has achieved commendable progress over the years in reducing child mortality and the incidences of [HIV/AIDS](/HIV/AIDS), [malaria](/Malaria), and other diseases, the country has been "performing dismally" in efforts to reduce [maternal mortality](/Maternal_mortality) and promote [gender equality](/Gender_equality) &#91;85&#93;. Furthermore, [female genital mutilation](/Female_genital_mutilation) (FGM), while not widely practiced across the nation, is regrettably still present in some localized communities &#91;129&#93;.

In the 2024 [Global Hunger Index](/Global_Hunger_Index) (GHI), [Malawi](/Malawi) registered a score of 21.9, a figure that unequivocally indicates a serious level of hunger within the country. This places [Malawi](/Malawi) at the 93rd position out of 127 countries ranked &#91;130&#93;, a stark reminder of the ongoing struggle for food security.

### Education

Public expenditure on education in [Southern Africa](/Southern_Africa) as a share of [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product), 2012 or closest year &#91;105&#93;. A chart displaying investment, a clear indicator of national priorities.

* Main article: [Education in Malawi](/Education_in_Malawi)

A pivotal reform in [Malawi's](/Malawi) education sector occurred in 1994 when the government introduced free primary education for all Malawian children. This commitment to universal access was further solidified with the passage of the Revised Education Act in 2012, making primary education compulsory. As a direct consequence of these policies, enrollment rates for primary schools witnessed a significant surge, climbing from 58% in 1992 to an impressive 75% in 2007. The retention of students also improved, with the percentage of those who began standard one and successfully completed standard five rising from 64% in 1992 to 86% in 2006. According to data from the [World Bank](/World_Bank), youth literacy rates also demonstrated positive growth, increasing from 68% in 2000 to 75% in 2015 &#91;131&#93;. This notable improvement is primarily attributed to a combination of enhanced learning materials available in schools, better physical infrastructure, and the implementation of feeding programs throughout the school system, all contributing to a more conducive learning environment &#91;85&#93;.

However, the educational journey for many Malawian students becomes more challenging beyond primary school. Attendance in secondary school drops considerably, to approximately 25%, with attendance rates being only marginally higher for males &#91;132&#93; &#91;133&#93;. This decline suggests significant barriers to accessing higher levels of education. Furthermore, dropout rates are regrettably higher for girls than for boys &#91;134&#93;, indicating persistent gender disparities within the education system.

The structure of education in [Malawi](/Malawi) is broadly divided into three stages: eight years of primary education, followed by four years of secondary school, and finally, four years of university-level study. The country is served by four public universities, which are critical institutions for higher learning: [Mzuzu University](/Mzuzu_University) (MZUNI), [Lilongwe University of Agriculture and Natural Resources](/Lilongwe_University_of_Agriculture_and_Natural_Resources) (LUANAR), the venerable [University of Malawi](/University_of_Malawi) (UNIMA), and the [Malawi University of Science and Technology](/Malawi_University_of_Science_and_Technology) (MUST). In addition to these public institutions, there are also several private universities, including Livingstonia, Malawi Lakeview, and the Catholic University of Malawi. The standard entry requirement for university admission is the attainment of six credits on the [Malawi School Certificate of Education](/Malawi_School_Certificate_of_Education), which is generally considered equivalent to [O levels](/Ordinary_Level) &#91;135&#93;.

## Women in Malawi

The Mbawemi Women's group in [Malawi](/Malawi) learning the intricate process of transforming beeswax into candles, a demonstration of economic empowerment and traditional skills.

Examining the ratio of male to female students reveals that women's access to schooling in [Malawi](/Malawi) initially begins on par with that of men &#91;136&#93;, a promising start. However, this parity unfortunately does not persist. Female students in [Malawi](/Malawi) experience consistent declines in enrollment and retention as they age &#91;136&#93;, indicating systemic challenges that disproportionately affect girls' progression through the education system. The [life expectancy](/Life_expectancy) for women in [Malawi](/Malawi) was approximately 58 years in 2010, showing an improvement to 66 years by 2017 &#91;137&#93;. Despite these gains, the [maternal mortality rate](/Maternal_mortality) in [Malawi](/Malawi) remains particularly low compared with other countries at similar levels of development &#91;138&#93;, a complex statistic that may reflect both progress in certain healthcare areas and persistent underlying issues.

In a positive legal development, the inheritance rights in [Malawi](/Malawi) are legally equal for both genders, applying to children and surviving spouses alike &#91;139&#93;, a crucial step towards gender equity. However, disparities persist in the employment sector. A higher percentage of the male population is employed, and while the female population has a higher total employed population, their unemployment rate is very similar &#91;140&#93; &#91;further explanation needed](/Wikipedia:Please_clarify) &#91;140&#93;. This employment gap is further reflected in wages in [Malawi](/Malawi) &#91;141&#93;. For context, [Rwanda](/Rwanda), the highest-ranked [sub-Saharan state](/Sub-Saharan_Africa), scored a 0.791 on a 0–1 scale in gender equality metrics, whereas [Malawi](/Malawi) scored 0.664 &#91;141&#93;, indicating a significant, albeit improving, disparity.

Women's participation in national politics has historically been weaker than men's, largely attributed to entrenched stereotypes that limit their perceived roles and capabilities &#91;142&#93;. This limited political participation is further exacerbated by the influence of "gatekeepers," individuals or groups who control access to the vital resources necessary to successfully win elections and maintain seats in parliament &#91;143&#93; &#91;144&#93;. This systemic barrier directly correlates with the limited number of women holding political office. Despite these obstacles, the national parliament has appointed female members to various seats, and over 20% of the total seats in parliament are currently held by women &#91;145&#93;, a slow but steady increase towards more equitable representation.

## Military

* Main article: [Malawian Defence Force](/Malawian_Defence_Force)

A [Malawian female soldier](/Women_in_the_military), a testament to the evolving roles within the nation's armed forces.

[Malawi](/Malawi) maintains a relatively modest standing military, known as the [Malawian Defence Force](/Malawian_Defence_Force), comprising approximately 25,000 personnel. This force is strategically organized into distinct army, navy, and air force elements, each with specialized roles and responsibilities. The origins of the [Malawi](/Malawi) army can be traced back to the [British colonial units](/British_Army) that were established in the region prior to the nation's [independence](/Independence). Today, the army is structured with two rifle regiments and one parachute regiment, forming the backbone of its ground forces.

The [Malawi Air Force](/Malawi_Air_Force) was established with valuable assistance from [Germany](/Germany) in 1976. It operates a small but essential fleet of transport aircraft and multi-purpose helicopters, providing crucial logistical support and limited aerial capabilities. The [Malawian Navy](/Malawi_Navy) was formed in the early 1970s, benefiting from Portuguese support.